Dialogue: 10,0:00:31.90,0:00:36.34,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa Toyohiko, the father \Nof the cooperative movement, {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cooperative}
Dialogue: 10,0:00:36.34,0:00:43.18,Narrator,,0,0,0,,was a great religious man, thinker, \Nnovelist, scientist, and social activist.
Dialogue: 10,0:00:43.18,0:00:47.95,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Until his death at the age of 72 in 1960,
Dialogue: 10,0:00:47.95,0:00:52.69,Narrator,,0,0,0,,at his home in Kamikitazawa, Setagaya Ward, Tokyo, his life was marked by great turmoil.
Dialogue: 10,0:00:52.69,0:00:57.59,Narrator,,0,0,0,,His is a history befitting \Na world-renowned figure born in Japan.
Dialogue: 10,0:00:57.59,0:01:01.80,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa Toyohiko was born on July 10, 1888,
Dialogue: 10,0:01:01.80,0:01:06.37,Narrator,,0,0,0,,in the port city of Kobe, Hyogo Prefecture, \Nto a concubine mother.
Dialogue: 10,0:01:06.37,0:01:11.51,Narrator,,0,0,0,,He spent his youth in hardship, burdened \Nby his father’s demise and his family’s downfall.
Dialogue: 10,0:01:11.51,0:01:16.28,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Until April 1900, \Nwhen he met Dr. Harry W. Myers,
Dialogue: 10,0:01:16.28,0:01:21.93,Narrator,,0,0,0,,an American Christian missionary teacher, \Nwhile attending Tokushima Middle School. {https://maps.app.goo.gl/x5ktSk7bqG6tf2mg6}
Dialogue: 10,0:01:21.93,0:01:27.94,Narrtop,,0,0,0,,This fateful encounter with Dr. Harry W. Myers \Ndetermined the whole life of Kagawa Toyohiko.
Dialogue: 10,0:01:28.76,0:01:32.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Brother, can I move to live with \Nan American missionary to learn English?
Dialogue: 10,0:01:32.94,0:01:36.96,Default,,0,0,0,,A missionary?! No way! \NHe'll convert you to Christianity!
Dialogue: 10,0:01:36.96,0:01:38.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Is something wrong with Christianity?
Dialogue: 10,0:01:38.95,0:01:40.77,Default,,0,0,0,,We have Buddhism right here in Japan!
Dialogue: 10,0:01:40.77,0:01:43.95,Default,,0,0,0,,I can’t let my kin become Christian—\Nit goes against our national identity! {Kokutai is a politically loaded word in the Japanese language, translatable as "sovereign", "national identity; national essence; national character" or "national polity; body politic; national entity; basis for the Emperor's sovereignty; Japanese constitution".}
Dialogue: 10,0:01:44.34,0:01:46.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Japan doesn't have a monopoly on salvation! {lit: seeking after truth​  is worldwide; common to the whole world; universal}
Dialogue: 10,0:01:46.74,0:01:47.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Who do you think you are?!
Dialogue: 10,0:01:48.44,0:01:50.98,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Shortly thereafter, the Kagawa family
Dialogue: 10,0:01:50.98,0:01:55.62,Narrator,,0,0,0,,went bankrupt due to his brother's reckless business ambitions and lavish lifestyle.
Dialogue: 10,0:01:56.38,0:02:00.59,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The creditors pounced on them, \Nand even the family estate had to be auctioned off. {/fell into others' hands}
Dialogue: 10,0:02:01.29,0:02:05.53,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Ultimately his older sister and younger brothers \Nwere all sent into apprenticeship. {/to work as servants.}
Dialogue: 10,0:02:06.43,0:02:10.73,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Having lost everything, \NToyohiko embarked on a spiritual quest {lit: went looking for his heart's wharf; quay; landing-stage}
Dialogue: 10,0:02:10.73,0:02:13.66,Narrator,,0,0,0,,and asked Dr. Myers \Nto baptize him at his parish.
Dialogue: 10,0:02:14.40,0:02:18.71,Narrator,,0,0,0,,It was February of 1904, \Nwhen Kagawa was 16 years old.
Dialogue: 10,0:02:18.99,0:02:24.26,Narrator,,0,0,0,,In March 1905, he graduated \Nfrom Tokushima Middle School.
Dialogue: 10,0:02:22.99,0:02:25.25,Top,,0,0,0,,Congratulations, Toyohiko.
Dialogue: 10,0:02:25.25,0:02:28.00,Default,,0,0,0,,So what are you going to do \Nafter middle school?
Dialogue: 10,0:02:28.00,0:02:33.00,Default,,0,0,0,,I want to join the Meiji Gakuin University in Tokyo \Nand become an evangelist. {evangelist; evangelistic worker - I guess that's specifically christian as opposed to "theologian" and such}
Dialogue: 10,0:02:33.00,0:02:35.96,Default,,0,0,0,,An evangelist? Are you stupid?!
Dialogue: 10,0:02:35.96,0:02:40.04,Default,,0,0,0,,We won’t tolerate deranged Christian fanatics under this roof! Get out! {kabure = crazy about; having an affectation concerning all things surrounding something (esp. a language, a culture, etc.)​}
Dialogue: 10,0:02:40.04,0:02:44.13,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Now that even his uncle’s kicked him out, \Nhe’s been left utterly alone in the world. {a person without a single relative}
Dialogue: 10,0:02:44.13,0:02:47.03,Narrator,,0,0,0,,He had nowhere to turn \Nbut Missionary Meyers’s place.
Dialogue: 10,0:02:47.03,0:02:48.69,Default,,0,0,0,,That's regrettable.
Dialogue: 10,0:02:48.69,0:02:51.71,Default,,0,0,0,,But I don't want you to worry,\Nyou can stay here from today on.
Dialogue: 10,0:02:51.71,0:02:53.07,Default,,0,0,0,,T-Teacher!
Dialogue: 10,0:02:57.54,0:03:02.01,Narrator,,0,0,0,,In April 1905, Kagawa moved to Tokyo.
Dialogue: 10,0:03:02.01,0:03:06.19,Narrator,,0,0,0,,At the time, Japan was in the second year \Nof the Russo-Japanese War.
Dialogue: 10,0:03:06.19,0:03:09.46,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Tokyo, the capital,\N was steeped in militaristic fervor.
Dialogue: 10,0:03:09.46,0:03:14.16,Narrator,,0,0,0,,When Kagawa entered Meiji Gakuin University in Shiba-Shirogane,
Dialogue: 10,0:03:14.16,0:03:17.21,Narrator,,0,0,0,,his passion for life was rekindled in his heart. {being deeply moved emotionally; excitement; passion; inspiration; deep emotion; strong impression}
Dialogue: 10,0:03:17.21,0:03:23.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Jesus, please cleanse those corrupt souls \Nand set the world straight again. Amen. {lit: wipe away the hearts that got dirty and restore the gods of heaven and earth​}
Dialogue: 10,0:03:23.09,0:03:25.24,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa holed himself up in the library
Dialogue: 10,0:03:25.24,0:03:29.74,Narrator,,0,0,0,,and read through thousands of books, \None volume a day, without fail.
Dialogue: 10,0:03:29.74,0:03:33.68,Narrator,,0,0,0,,There were many untranslated works, \Nbut Kagawa could digest even them without trouble. {book in its original language (esp. a European language)}
Dialogue: 10,0:03:33.68,0:03:36.05,Default,,0,0,0,,Kagawa, you’ve got to attend \Nat least a few lectures—
Dialogue: 10,0:03:36.05,0:03:38.10,Default,,0,0,0,,you won’t graduate \Nif your attendance is too low.
Dialogue: 10,0:03:38.10,0:03:40.96,Default,,0,0,0,,I don’t need to sit through those lectures—
Dialogue: 10,0:03:40.96,0:03:44.11,Default,,0,0,0,,everything they teach there, \NI’ve already learned from Dr. Myers.
Dialogue: 10,0:03:46.71,0:03:51.40,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The following year, Kagawa transferred from Meiji Gakuin University to Kobe New School. {can't find this one, probably some small religious school}
Dialogue: 10,0:03:51.40,0:03:55.94,Narrator,,0,0,0,,He then helped out with missionary work \Nin Aichi Prefecture for six months.
Dialogue: 10,0:03:55.94,0:04:03.04,Narrator,,0,0,0,,There he met Pastor Nagao of the Toyohashi Church, \Nwho fought for peasants and the poor. {https://maps.app.goo.gl/rcXFu7t3aRRZP25M8 ; can't find the guy himself}
Dialogue: 10,0:04:03.04,0:04:06.75,Narrator,,0,0,0,,In later years, Kagawa said this about Nagao:
Dialogue: 10,0:04:06.75,0:04:09.62,Narrator,,0,0,0,,"Until the day he died, \Nhe kept crying out in prayer
Dialogue: 10,0:04:09.62,0:04:13.02,Narrator,,0,0,0,,that the gospel might reach \Nthe poor and the peasants. {lit: for the gospel to be transmitted/preached to ... - no clue how that's supposed to help them}
Dialogue: 10,0:04:13.69,0:04:18.14,Narrator,,0,0,0,,It was from Nagao that I inherited \Nmy love for the peasants."
Dialogue: 10,0:04:20.49,0:04:23.15,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa was staying in Nagao's rundown hut,
Dialogue: 10,0:04:23.15,0:04:25.77,Narrator,,0,0,0,,and spent the days preaching passionately.
Dialogue: 10,0:04:25.77,0:04:27.03,Default,,0,0,0,,God is love!
Dialogue: 10,0:04:27.03,0:04:32.59,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm not saying love is some invisible deity, \Nbut love is the manifestation of the divine in us. {/where there's love, god appears}
Dialogue: 10,0:04:32.59,0:04:33.67,Default,,0,0,0,,God is love!
Dialogue: 10,0:04:34.16,0:04:38.31,Narrator,,0,0,0,,During this period, a lung disease \Nundermined Kagawa's health.
Dialogue: 10,0:04:38.31,0:04:42.35,Narrator,,0,0,0,,His slight fever never subsided \Nand it seemed to everyone like an incurable disease. {lit: the signs of an incurable illness were showing - ???}
Dialogue: 10,0:04:43.18,0:04:45.72,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Eventually, he started coughing blood badly.
Dialogue: 10,0:04:45.72,0:04:49.22,Narrator,,0,0,0,,His breathing was labored, \Nand his fever climbed past 40 degrees—
Dialogue: 10,0:04:49.22,0:04:51.66,Narrator,,0,0,0,,eventually, even the doctor gave up on him.
Dialogue: 10,0:04:51.66,0:04:56.80,Narrator,,0,0,0,,But Kagawa was not \Nin the slightest afraid of death.
Dialogue: 10,0:04:56.80,0:05:01.15,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Rather, he remained completely still, \Nas if he had returned to his mother's womb.
Dialogue: 10,0:05:01.64,0:05:05.71,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Suddenly, spiritual light \Nenveloped his whole body. {think this is not literal but rather like "the holy light shone on him figuratively"}
Dialogue: 10,0:05:05.71,0:05:09.41,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Mysteriously, his breathing gradually improved,
Dialogue: 10,0:05:09.41,0:05:12.68,Narrator,,0,0,0,,his fever subsided, \Nand his complexion returned to normal.
Dialogue: 10,0:05:12.68,0:05:15.72,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa sought a quiet place \Nto recuperate from his tuberculosis,
Dialogue: 10,0:05:15.72,0:05:18.69,Narrator,,0,0,0,,and he found it in the fishing village \Nof Gamagori, Aichi Prefecture. {https://maps.app.goo.gl/yAt9719nEdJUcmmW8}{???}
Dialogue: 10,0:05:19.32,0:05:22.17,Narrator,,0,0,0,,It was January 1908.
Dialogue: 10,0:05:22.66,0:05:25.46,Narrator,,0,0,0,,While he continued \Nto recuperate here in poverty,
Dialogue: 10,0:05:25.46,0:05:30.18,Narrator,,0,0,0,,he began writing a novel that depicted his lonely life—"Mimicking the Pigeon." {鳩の真似 - don't think even the title has been translated before}
Dialogue: 10,0:05:30.96,0:05:35.67,Narrator,,0,0,0,,By the time the cherry blossoms were falling, \Nthe novel was completed.
Dialogue: 10,0:05:36.16,0:05:42.58,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa then traveled to Tokyo for the first time \Nin a year to have Shimazaki Touson read his novel. {meaning he hasn't been there for about a year}{https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T%C5%8Dson_Shimazaki}
Dialogue: 10,0:05:43.34,0:05:48.55,Narrator,,0,0,0,,By then Touson had already published his "Broken Commandment," taking the literary world by storm, {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Broken_Commandment}{also hakai itself means "offense against the Buddhist commandments (offence)"}{the last part lit: making a dashing appearance in the literature world}
Dialogue: 10,0:05:48.55,0:05:51.20,Narrator,,0,0,0,,and was serializing "Spring" \Nin Asahi Shinbun newspaper. {https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E6%98%A5_(%E5%B0%8F%E8%AA%AC)}
Dialogue: 10,0:05:51.20,0:05:55.22,Default,,0,0,0,,This is a novel I wrote, please read it.
Dialogue: 10,0:05:55.22,0:05:59.26,Top,,0,0,0,,Look, you can't write a novel \Nby straight-up describing life. {looking up to; revering - probably this}
Dialogue: 10,0:05:59.26,0:06:03.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Novels are art, so they must have \Na spark of emotion to them. {insight; flash (of inspiration, wit, etc.)​}
Dialogue: 10,0:06:04.21,0:06:07.73,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Touson rejected his "Mimicking the Pigeon."{sending back; return to sender}
Dialogue: 10,0:06:08.84,0:06:11.81,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Later, in 1920, "Mimicking the Pigeon"
Dialogue: 10,0:06:11.81,0:06:15.94,Narrator,,0,0,0,,would still be published by Kaizosha, \Nretitled as "Across the Death-line." {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kaiz%C5%8Dsha}
Dialogue: 10,0:06:16.44,0:06:23.22,Narrator,,0,0,0,,It became an unprecedented bestseller, going through 50, then 100, and eventually 150 printings. {/editions}
Dialogue: 10,0:06:24.32,0:06:28.66,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The day before Christmas in December 1909,
Dialogue: 10,0:06:28.66,0:06:33.86,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa became a resident of the slums \Nof Shinkawa, Fukiai, in Kobe. {https://maps.app.goo.gl/XE9fCSospNEy8EtGA}
Dialogue: 10,0:06:36.26,0:06:43.14,Narrator,,0,0,0,,He believed the damage from tuberculosis \Nhad left him with no more than three years to live.
Dialogue: 10,0:06:43.14,0:06:44.97,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Figuring he was going to die anyway,
Dialogue: 10,0:06:44.97,0:06:50.41,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa chose to live among those \Nwith no food, no clothes, and nowhere to sleep.
Dialogue: 10,0:06:50.41,0:06:56.68,Narrator,,0,0,0,,He had resolved to keep preaching on their behalf until his life burned out—and to die doing just that.
Dialogue: 10,0:06:58.30,0:07:00.49,Default,,0,0,0,,A new life begins for me.
Dialogue: 10,0:07:00.49,0:07:02.32,Default,,0,0,0,,I understand God bestowed it unto me. {maybe as a trial of his faith idk}
Dialogue: 10,0:07:02.72,0:07:07.31,Default,,0,0,0,,God, give me strength to keep doing my best for the poor. Amen.
Dialogue: 10,0:07:08.60,0:07:15.20,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Life in the Kobe slums taught Kagawa Toyohiko the many different ways people struggle to live.
Dialogue: 10,0:07:15.20,0:07:20.41,Narrator,,0,0,0,,For Kagawa—who would later become a leading voice in labor and peasant movements—
Dialogue: 10,0:07:20.41,0:07:25.00,Narrator,,0,0,0,,this way of life was a formative experience in his struggle against social injustice.
Dialogue: 10,0:07:26.11,0:07:29.58,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Soon, together with the people who gathered around him,
Dialogue: 10,0:07:29.58,0:07:33.99,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa established a church \Nin a six-tatami room he was renting.
Dialogue: 10,0:07:33.99,0:07:37.34,Narrator,,0,0,0,,It became the base for the \NKobe Jesus Society, organized later. {about:blank}
Dialogue: 10,0:07:37.92,0:07:45.37,Narrator,,0,0,0,,In the summer of 1911, Kagawa began working at the Fukuin Printing Company as a hymns teacher. {hymn; psalm}
Dialogue: 10,0:07:46.03,0:07:52.01,Narrator,,0,0,0,,There Kagawa met \Nhis lifelong partner Shibata Haru. {can't find anything about her, but maybe partner is not strong enough a word since it's his wife}
Dialogue: 10,0:07:52.01,0:07:59.36,Narrator,,0,0,0,,They got married on May 22nd, 1913, \Nat Kobe Church on Shimoyamate Street. {https://maps.app.goo.gl/jRDBdkGooWzTrRT77}
Dialogue: 10,0:07:59.91,0:08:05.45,Narrator,,0,0,0,,On August 2nd of the following year, 1914, \NKagawa departed for America.
Dialogue: 10,0:08:06.49,0:08:12.03,Narrtop,,0,0,0,,The purpose was to raise funds to create \Na settlement in the slums of Shinkawa, Kobe.
Dialogue: 10,0:08:13.26,0:08:14.96,Narrtop,,0,0,0,,What is a settlement?
Dialogue: 10,0:08:14.96,0:08:20.37,Narrtop,,0,0,0,,It is a social institution that seeks to improve \Nthe lives of workers living in slums.
Dialogue: 10,0:08:20.37,0:08:24.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Haru, I'm going to America to earn money.
Dialogue: 10,0:08:24.30,0:08:27.14,Default,,0,0,0,,There, I'll get my doctorate \Nand earn some money.
Dialogue: 10,0:08:27.14,0:08:31.36,Default,,0,0,0,,With that funding, we’ll build a state-of-the-art hospital right here in Shinkawa. {lit: equipped with all medical facilities}
Dialogue: 10,0:08:32.38,0:08:36.55,Narrtop,,0,0,0,,To cover his travel expenses, he borrowed money from Dr. Myers and his acquaintances,
Dialogue: 10,0:08:36.55,0:08:39.37,Narrtop,,0,0,0,,and took on translation work.
Dialogue: 10,0:08:39.37,0:08:41.76,Narrator,,0,0,0,,At Princeton University in the US,
Dialogue: 10,0:08:41.76,0:08:46.63,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa studied experimental psychology, \Nmathematics and natural sciences.
Dialogue: 10,0:08:46.63,0:08:51.38,Narrator,,0,0,0,,He thus spent his days \Nat Princeton University studying hard. {???}
Dialogue: 10,0:08:51.93,0:08:54.17,Narrator,,0,0,0,,During his second year at university,
Dialogue: 10,0:08:54.17,0:08:59.77,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa completed Princeton Theological Seminary’s four-year coursework in only two years.
Dialogue: 10,0:08:59.77,0:09:03.38,Narrator,,0,0,0,,He was granted a Bachelor of Divinity degree in theology.
Dialogue: 10,0:09:04.08,0:09:09.08,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa went to see Water Street, \Nthe slum district of New York.
Dialogue: 10,0:09:09.08,0:09:12.92,Thought,,0,0,0,,This is no different \Nfrom the Shinkawa Slum City in Kobe!
Dialogue: 10,0:09:12.92,0:09:14.49,Thought,,0,0,0,,What is a worker?
Dialogue: 10,0:09:14.49,0:09:16.82,Thought,,0,0,0,,Is worker synonymous to "pauper" now?! {the poor; the needy; the destitute}
Dialogue: 10,0:09:16.82,0:09:19.66,Thought,,0,0,0,,If workers are unemployed, \Nthey can only end up in poverty! {??}
Dialogue: 10,0:09:20.33,0:09:25.03,Thought,,0,0,0,,All the relief efforts so far will never truly solve the problem of poverty in the long run.
Dialogue: 10,0:09:25.03,0:09:28.77,Thought,,0,0,0,,The key to solving this problem \Nlies in addressing the workers’ plight.
Dialogue: 10,0:09:29.42,0:09:31.77,Thought,,0,0,0,,The workers' poverty—that's it!
Dialogue: 10,0:09:31.77,0:09:36.24,Thought,,0,0,0,,Unless the proletariat join forces and rise up to free themselves,
Dialogue: 10,0:09:36.24,0:09:37.74,Thought,,0,0,0,,who’s going to help them?! {??}
Dialogue: 10,0:09:38.41,0:09:40.18,Thought,,0,0,0,,The workers must unite!
Dialogue: 10,0:09:40.18,0:09:44.69,Thought,,0,0,0,,Each one of them is weak alone, but once they band together as a union, they become a powerful force—
Dialogue: 10,0:09:44.69,0:09:46.85,Thought,,0,0,0,,strong enough to win their own freedom!
Dialogue: 10,0:09:47.44,0:09:54.46,Narrator,,0,0,0,,In May 1917, Kagawa returned from the US\Nto the slums of Shinkawa, Kobe
Dialogue: 10,0:09:54.46,0:09:58.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's build our own factory—\Nfor workers, by workers!
Dialogue: 10,0:09:58.93,0:10:04.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Buying daily necessities cheaply is another way \Nto protect workers' livelihoods.
Dialogue: 10,0:10:04.27,0:10:07.38,Default,,0,0,0,,To do that, we need to link consumers and producers directly—
Dialogue: 10,0:10:07.38,0:10:09.74,Default,,0,0,0,,cutting out the leech of the middlemen.
Dialogue: 10,0:10:09.74,0:10:14.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Consumers will form a cooperative \Nand buy from the producers—personally.
Dialogue: 10,0:10:14.88,0:10:22.49,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa also drew on his Christian connections to launch a consumer cooperative in Osaka.
Dialogue: 10,0:10:22.49,0:10:25.93,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The following year, the Kobe Consumer Cooperative was born.
Dialogue: 10,0:10:25.93,0:10:28.56,Narrator,,0,0,0,,It would become the predecessor of the Nada {Livelihood }Cooperative,
Dialogue: 10,0:10:28.56,0:10:31.51,Narrator,,0,0,0,,a pioneer of the consumer movement in Japan. {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Co-op_Kobe}
Dialogue: 10,0:10:31.51,0:10:37.64,Narrator,,0,0,0,,In April of the following year, 1918, \NKagawa gave a passionate speech
Dialogue: 10,0:10:37.64,0:10:41.79,Narrator,,0,0,0,,at the 5th Fraternity Association's General Rally  \Nat the Tennoji Public Hall in Osaka. {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Y%C5%ABaikai}
Dialogue: 10,0:10:41.79,0:10:44.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Why are workers usually poor?
Dialogue: 10,0:10:44.79,0:10:48.38,Default,,0,0,0,,The first cause is drinking—\Nmost of them do physically demanding work. {I don't see the connection tbh lol}
Dialogue: 10,0:10:48.38,0:10:53.62,Default,,0,0,0,,The second cause is illness—once they get sick, they lose their jobs and fall into destitution.
Dialogue: 10,0:10:53.62,0:10:59.23,Default,,0,0,0,,The third cause is injury—workers who operate machinery can’t avoid getting hurt.
Dialogue: 10,0:10:59.23,0:11:01.63,Default,,0,0,0,,The fourth cause is the lack of social security— {lit: instability in life}
Dialogue: 10,0:11:01.63,0:11:04.46,Default,,0,0,0,,economic tides can shift at any moment, \Nand you'll lose your job.
Dialogue: 10,0:11:04.46,0:11:08.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Fifth: workers are not slaves—they’re free!
Dialogue: 10,0:11:08.37,0:11:10.70,Default,,0,0,0,,And the very fact that, despite their freedom,
Dialogue: 10,0:11:10.70,0:11:14.82,Default,,0,0,0,,they still can’t make a living points to a major flaw \Nin the social system. Let’s not forget that!
Dialogue: 10,0:11:15.38,0:11:19.28,Narrator,,0,0,0,,He strongly advocated for a mutual aid system \Nand the cooperative movement.
Dialogue: 10,0:11:19.71,0:11:22.48,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa Toyohiko, the father \Nof the farmers’ cooperative movement,
Dialogue: 10,0:11:22.48,0:11:24.83,Narrator,,0,0,0,,was already convinced of that \Nwhen he gave this speech.
Dialogue: 10,0:11:25.39,0:11:28.35,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Two full years have passed \Nsince he joined the labor movement.
Dialogue: 10,0:11:28.35,0:11:31.53,Narrator,,0,0,0,,At the age of 32, Kagawa Toyohiko \Nbecame the leader
Dialogue: 10,0:11:31.53,0:11:34.99,Narrator,,0,0,0,,of the Japanese Federation of Labor \Nin the Kansai region. {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_Federation_of_Labour}
Dialogue: 10,0:11:35.63,0:11:39.03,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The worker is a human person, \Nnot a commodity.
Dialogue: 10,0:11:39.70,0:11:45.86,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa’s ideas gave workers a sense of pride \Nand struck a chord with many of them.
Dialogue: 10,0:11:46.34,0:11:50.54,Narrator,,0,0,0,,It was also around this time that a conference of Christian clergy was held in Japan.
Dialogue: 10,0:11:50.54,0:11:54.88,Narrator,,0,0,0,,A new religious movement organization, \Nthe Friends of Jesus movement, was formed. {iesunotomokai}
Dialogue: 10,0:11:54.88,0:11:56.98,Thought,,0,0,0,,Is this also the Lord’s guidance?
Dialogue: 10,0:11:56.98,0:12:00.09,Thought,,0,0,0,,I must return to the spiritual movement \Nand to evangelism. {fuck knows what he means ????}
Dialogue: 10,0:12:00.09,0:12:02.52,Narrator,,0,0,0,,When Kagawa saw that the labor movement
Dialogue: 10,0:12:02.52,0:12:06.29,Narrator,,0,0,0,,could now stand on its own, he felt an increasing pull back toward the spiritual movement—
Dialogue: 10,0:12:06.29,0:12:09.10,Narrator,,0,0,0,,and a certain thought kept returning to him. {????? fuck knows what they meant by "when it was time to be released from"}
Dialogue: 10,0:12:09.70,0:12:12.73,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Namely, the sight of rural areas \Nand the faces of farmers
Dialogue: 10,0:12:12.73,0:12:15.89,Narrator,,0,0,0,,that he saw in his childhood \Nin Tokushima Prefecture.
Dialogue: 10,0:12:15.89,0:12:19.51,Thought,,0,0,0,,We must save the farmers! \NExtend to them the loving grace.
Dialogue: 10,0:12:19.51,0:12:22.21,Thought,,0,0,0,,We can build an ideal society \Nwith the hands of farmers.
Dialogue: 10,0:12:22.89,0:12:25.81,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The Japan Agricultural Cooperative
Dialogue: 10,0:12:25.81,0:12:31.85,Narrator,,0,0,0,,was born on April 9th, 1922, \Nat the Christian Youth Hall in Kobe.
Dialogue: 10,0:12:31.85,0:12:38.92,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The day before, 120 farmer representatives from rural areas across the country had rushed to Kobe.
Dialogue: 10,0:12:38.92,0:12:43.63,Narrator,,0,0,0,,In every sun-weathered face held high, \Nyou could see the yearning for Sakura Sogoro,
Dialogue: 10,0:12:43.63,0:12:45.87,Narrator,,0,0,0,,the folk hero of the Taisho era. {lit: trying to become sakura sogoro ... the tanned faces were stretched out}{https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sakura_S%C5%8Dgor%C5%8D - eyyy, the second show we're doing about him}
Dialogue: 10,0:12:46.67,0:12:49.87,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The founding meeting \Nended in a great success.
Dialogue: 10,0:12:49.87,0:12:53.71,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The farmers' movement also helped strengthen industrial cooperatives,
Dialogue: 10,0:12:53.71,0:12:58.11,Narrator,,0,0,0,,which eventually expanded to include sales, purchasing, credit, and even medical care divisions. {???}
Dialogue: 10,0:12:58.11,0:13:03.55,Narrator,,0,0,0,,This general meeting laid the first cornerstone in Kagawa Toyohiko's grand vision
Dialogue: 10,0:13:03.55,0:13:10.66,Narrator,,0,0,0,,to cultivate mutual aid organizations and create an ideal society in rural Japan.
Dialogue: 10,0:13:10.66,0:13:13.89,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The founding of the Japan Agricultural Cooperative marked a turning point,
Dialogue: 10,0:13:13.89,0:13:18.43,Narrator,,0,0,0,,igniting the farmers' movement \Nas it swept across the countryside like wildfire.
Dialogue: 10,0:13:18.43,0:13:22.07,Narrator,,0,0,0,,At the same time, Kagawa Toyohiko was more active than ever.
Dialogue: 10,0:13:22.54,0:13:28.28,Narrator,,0,0,0,,He gave Bible lectures, taught at a workers' school, \Nsupported a consumer cooperative,
Dialogue: 10,0:13:28.28,0:13:33.14,Narrator,,0,0,0,,and, finally, as a man of letters, \Ntoiled endlessly with pen in hand. {/literature man}
Dialogue: 10,0:13:35.05,0:13:39.69,Narrator,,0,0,0,,In December 1922, \NKagawa's first son Sumimoto is born.
Dialogue: 10,0:13:40.25,0:13:45.98,Narrator,,0,0,0,,But one day in January of the following year, 1923, \Nhe suddenly lost his sight due to repeated overwork.
Dialogue: 10,0:13:47.44,0:13:51.40,Narrator,,0,0,0,,But even so, he didn't stop giving lectures. {actually "writing/authoring"}
Dialogue: 10,0:13:51.40,0:13:55.80,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa's eyesight kept deteriorating, \Nto the point where he was on the verge of going blind.
Dialogue: 10,0:13:55.80,0:13:58.00,Narrator,,0,0,0,,At last, he was forced into hospitalization. {meaning someone persuaded him}
Dialogue: 10,0:13:58.84,0:14:04.01,Narrator,,0,0,0,,His wife Haru carefully read the Bible \Nand the Philosophical Books newspaper for him.
Dialogue: 10,0:14:04.01,0:14:07.85,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa was determined to keep up \Nwith the changing tides of the world.
Dialogue: 10,0:14:07.85,0:14:13.05,Thought,,0,0,0,,Job was hit with seven disasters, \Nbut he endured it and never gave up on his faith. {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Job_(biblical_figure)}
Dialogue: 10,0:14:13.05,0:14:18.09,Thought,,0,0,0,,He didn't run away from pain, \Nbut happily accepted all the pain in life.
Dialogue: 10,0:14:18.94,0:14:21.94,Narrator,,0,0,0,,In August, his eyes began improving.
Dialogue: 10,0:14:22.53,0:14:26.77,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The Universal Suffrage Law \Nwas enacted in March 1925.
Dialogue: 10,0:14:26.77,0:14:30.97,Default,,0,0,0,,That means we workers and farmers \Nwere given the right to vote too!
Dialogue: 10,0:14:30.97,0:14:35.51,Narrator,,0,0,0,,In March 1926, \Nthe Labor-Farmer Party was founded. {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Labour-Farmer_Party}
Dialogue: 10,0:14:35.51,0:14:39.96,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Sugiyama Motojiro was appointed chairman \Nwith Kagawa as the executive committee member. {https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E6%9D%89%E5%B1%B1%E5%85%83%E6%B2%BB%E9%83%8E}
Dialogue: 10,0:14:39.96,0:14:43.58,Default,,0,0,0,,I've founded this party, but I'm not going \Nto run for the Diet myself. {become parliamentarian; member of a congress}
Dialogue: 10,0:14:43.58,0:14:48.39,Default,,0,0,0,,With the spirit of Jesus Christ in my heart, I intend to serve the proletarian party from behind the scenes. {lowly position; bottom (of the ladder); obscurity}
Dialogue: 10,0:14:48.39,0:14:53.16,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Having said that, Kagawa continued \Nto live by those words for the rest of his life.
Dialogue: 10,0:14:53.16,0:14:59.57,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Both before and after the war, there was a fervent push to get Kagawa Toyohiko elected to the Diet,
Dialogue: 10,0:14:59.57,0:15:01.95,Narrator,,0,0,0,,but he never took office.
Dialogue: 10,0:15:01.95,0:15:06.94,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The Japan Agricultural Cooperative, which had now become the largest such organization in the country,
Dialogue: 10,0:15:06.94,0:15:12.20,Narrator,,0,0,0,,gave birth to the Labor-Farmer Party, \Nthe first unified proletarian party in Japan— {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japan_Labour-Farmer_Party}
Dialogue: 10,0:15:12.20,0:15:14.96,Narrator,,0,0,0,,a groundbreaking achievement \Nin the history of political parties.
Dialogue: 10,0:15:14.96,0:15:17.92,Narrator,,0,0,0,,However, even the \NLabor-Farmer Party soon became
Dialogue: 10,0:15:17.92,0:15:20.97,Narrator,,0,0,0,,a battleground for internal strife between left and right factions.
Dialogue: 10,0:15:20.97,0:15:26.16,Narrator,,0,0,0,,On February 1st, 1927, the Japan Agricultural Cooperative ultimately split
Dialogue: 10,0:15:26.16,0:15:28.93,Narrator,,0,0,0,,due to infighting among the proletarian parties.
Dialogue: 10,0:15:28.93,0:15:32.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Sugiyama-kun, let’s start a new farmers’ union.
Dialogue: 10,0:15:32.90,0:15:37.99,Default,,0,0,0,,One free of violence, free of internal feuds—\None that is grounded in political ethics.
Dialogue: 10,0:15:38.37,0:15:44.58,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Thus, with Sugiyama Motojiro as its chair, \Nthe All-Japan Farmers’ Union was established.
Dialogue: 10,0:15:45.24,0:15:50.58,Narrator,,0,0,0,,But Kagawa’s hope for this \Nnew farmers’ union was short-lived.
Dialogue: 10,0:15:50.58,0:15:53.00,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Leftist extremism began to seep in.
Dialogue: 10,0:15:53.92,0:15:58.69,Thought,,0,0,0,,Even the All-Japan Farmers’ Union \Nturned into a combative, militant organization.
Dialogue: 10,0:15:58.69,0:16:00.36,Thought,,0,0,0,,This is troubling.
Dialogue: 10,0:16:00.36,0:16:04.06,Thought,,0,0,0,,My struggle has also been derailed by these insane political movements.
Dialogue: 10,0:16:04.06,0:16:06.02,Thought,,0,0,0,,I must withdraw \Nfrom the proletarian party.
Dialogue: 10,0:16:06.02,0:16:08.67,Thought,,0,0,0,,But I am still a disciple of Jesus.
Dialogue: 10,0:16:08.67,0:16:10.02,Thought,,0,0,0,,I will never surrender like this!
Dialogue: 10,0:16:10.02,0:16:13.71,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The new battle Kagawa sought to fight against social evils
Dialogue: 10,0:16:13.71,0:16:16.44,Narrator,,0,0,0,,would now be through \Nthe Kingdom of God movement
Dialogue: 10,0:16:16.44,0:16:18.68,Narrator,,0,0,0,,rooted in the consumer \Ncooperative movement.
Dialogue: 10,0:16:19.65,0:16:23.40,Narrator,,0,0,0,,He aimed to liberate workers and farmers \Nthrough the teachings of God.
Dialogue: 10,0:16:24.32,0:16:29.01,Narrator,,0,0,0,,He prayed that by disseminating the idea of Jesus saving farmers, he'd rouse them to action. {???}
Dialogue: 10,0:16:29.01,0:16:31.73,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa Toyohiko, now distancing himself
Dialogue: 10,0:16:31.73,0:16:34.83,Narrator,,0,0,0,,from the proletarian party \Nto pursue the Kingdom of God,
Dialogue: 10,0:16:34.83,0:16:39.33,Narrator,,0,0,0,,established a Danish-style \Nfolk high school for farmers in Japan, {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Folk_high_school}
Dialogue: 10,0:16:39.33,0:16:43.67,Narrator,,0,0,0,,hoping to foster an agriculture \Nstrong enough to overcome hardship
Dialogue: 10,0:16:43.67,0:16:46.24,Narrator,,0,0,0,,through new forms of rural education.
Dialogue: 10,0:16:46.61,0:16:49.03,Narrator,,0,0,0,,That approach was called \Nthree-dimensional forestry. {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toyohiko_Kagawa#Three-dimensional_forestry}
Dialogue: 10,0:16:49.03,0:16:52.78,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa Toyohiko’s concept \Nof three-dimensional forestry
Dialogue: 10,0:16:52.78,0:16:55.75,Narrator,,0,0,0,,aimed to make use of Japan’s mountainous terrain—
Dialogue: 10,0:16:55.75,0:17:01.46,Narrator,,0,0,0,,which makes up 80% of the country and is one of the root causes of rural poverty—for food production.
Dialogue: 10,0:17:01.46,0:17:07.74,Narrtop,,0,0,0,,On January 9th, 1931, Kurokawa Taiichi \Nreceived a telegram from Kagawa Toyohiko.
Dialogue: 10,0:17:07.74,0:17:10.90,Narrtop,,0,0,0,,Kurokawa, who would later \Nserve as executive director
Dialogue: 10,0:17:10.90,0:17:13.97,Narrtop,,0,0,0,,of the National Federation of Consumers' Cooperatives
Dialogue: 10,0:17:13.97,0:17:17.27,Narrtop,,0,0,0,,and head the Tokyo Medical Cooperative, \Nwas 29 years old at the time.
Dialogue: 10,0:17:17.27,0:17:19.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Kurokawa-kun, I’m glad you could make it.
Dialogue: 10,0:17:19.57,0:17:24.04,Default,,0,0,0,,I’ve decided to start a medical cooperative. \NI’d like you to work on it together with Kidachi-kun.
Dialogue: 10,0:17:24.04,0:17:26.03,Default,,0,0,0,,A medical cooperative, Kidachi-san?
Dialogue: 10,0:17:26.03,0:17:29.82,Default,,0,0,0,,It's a hospital, modeled \Nafter a cooperative, it seems.
Dialogue: 10,0:17:29.82,0:17:35.04,Default,,0,0,0,,First, I’d like everyone to hear why I believe such a medical cooperative is necessary.
Dialogue: 10,0:17:35.04,0:17:37.22,Default,,0,0,0,,If we compare cities to the countryside,
Dialogue: 10,0:17:37.22,0:17:42.33,Default,,0,0,0,,data shows that the mortality rate in rural areas \Nis nearly double that of urban areas.
Dialogue: 10,0:17:42.33,0:17:46.67,Default,,0,0,0,,This means that poor laborers and farmers \Nare being abandoned by the medical system.
Dialogue: 10,0:17:46.67,0:17:49.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Rural areas in particular \Nhave become medical hellscapes.
Dialogue: 10,0:17:49.40,0:17:54.06,Default,,0,0,0,,My aim for this medical cooperative is to rescue these rural communities from that medical hell.
Dialogue: 10,0:17:54.06,0:17:59.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Since the Taisho era and throughout Showa, the number of villages with no doctor only increased.
Dialogue: 10,0:17:59.15,0:18:01.65,Default,,0,0,0,,And with that, \Nthe rural mortality rate kept rising.
Dialogue: 10,0:18:01.65,0:18:04.55,Default,,0,0,0,,How can such a thing be allowed \Nto transpire in a civilized nation?
Dialogue: 10,0:18:04.55,0:18:07.52,Default,,0,0,0,,There is only one way to save \Nrural Japan from its medical hell:
Dialogue: 10,0:18:07.52,0:18:11.59,Default,,0,0,0,,build healthcare facilities under the \NIndustrial Cooperative Act in farming villages.
Dialogue: 10,0:18:11.59,0:18:15.13,Default,,0,0,0,,The farmers themselves must create hospitals \Nthrough medical cooperatives.
Dialogue: 10,0:18:15.70,0:18:18.57,Default,,0,0,0,,A medical system based \Non cooperative principles
Dialogue: 10,0:18:18.57,0:18:24.00,Default,,0,0,0,,is different from a state-imposed system—\Nmembers and doctors alike share responsibility.
Dialogue: 10,0:18:24.00,0:18:27.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Everyone will strive \Nto fulfill their duties ethically—
Dialogue: 10,0:18:27.09,0:18:30.41,Default,,0,0,0,,that'll allow the medical services \Nto remain affordable.
Dialogue: 10,0:18:30.41,0:18:34.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Farmers will be able see doctors at low cost, and doctors will have no reason to flee the rural areas.
Dialogue: 10,0:18:34.98,0:18:39.65,Default,,0,0,0,,The way to banish medical hell from rural Japan \Nis to build medical cooperatives.
Dialogue: 10,0:18:40.10,0:18:42.76,Narrator,,0,0,0,,On May 11th, 1931,
Dialogue: 10,0:18:42.76,0:18:49.49,Narrator,,0,0,0,,a founding meeting for the Tokyo Medical Cooperative was held at the YMCA Hall in Kanda, Tokyo. {https://maps.app.goo.gl/yfBi8zbxyT5WCuBQ6}
Dialogue: 10,0:18:49.49,0:18:51.53,Narrator,,0,0,0,,150 people attended.
Dialogue: 10,0:18:51.53,0:18:56.12,Narrator,,0,0,0,,There, Kagawa passionately spoke on the goals \Nof the medical cooperative movement.
Dialogue: 10,0:18:56.12,0:19:00.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Medical treatment must be available \Nto protect the sanctity of human life,
Dialogue: 10,0:19:00.70,0:19:05.13,Default,,0,0,0,,regardless of wealth or social standing—\Nthat goes without saying.
Dialogue: 10,0:19:06.05,0:19:10.92,Narrator,,0,0,0,,On April 25th, 1932, \Nthe first general assembly
Dialogue: 10,0:19:10.92,0:19:15.49,Narrator,,0,0,0,,of the Tokyo Medical Cooperative \Nwas held at the YMCA Hall in Kanda, Tokyo.
Dialogue: 10,0:19:16.22,0:19:19.99,Narrator,,0,0,0,,That very same day, \Nat Osaka’s Central Public Hall, {https://maps.app.goo.gl/3JmYzYzUCqHpagQ56}
Dialogue: 10,0:19:19.99,0:19:24.10,Narrator,,0,0,0,,the 28th National Industrial Cooperative Conference was held,
Dialogue: 10,0:19:24.10,0:19:29.15,Narrator,,0,0,0,,and a five-year action plan \Nfor the cooperative was formulated.
Dialogue: 10,0:19:29.15,0:19:33.87,Narrator,,0,0,0,,On May 15th, 1932, \NPrime Minister Inukai was assassinated—
Dialogue: 10,0:19:33.87,0:19:35.91,Narrator,,0,0,0,,that would be called the May 15th Incident. {https://www.ndl.go.jp/modern/e/cha4/description02.html}
Dialogue: 10,0:19:35.91,0:19:41.65,Narrator,,0,0,0,,On July 9th, 1932, an inn was rented \Nin the 3rd Block of Shinjuku, Yotsuya Ward,
Dialogue: 10,0:19:41.65,0:19:44.08,Narrator,,0,0,0,,and so the Shinjuku Clinic was born.
Dialogue: 10,0:19:44.74,0:19:49.16,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Though small, it was a general hospital \Nwith departments for surgery, internal medicine,
Dialogue: 10,0:19:49.16,0:19:52.22,Narrator,,0,0,0,,pediatrics, obstetrics \Ngynecology, and dentistry.
Dialogue: 10,0:19:52.22,0:19:56.66,Thought,,0,0,0,,From this modest base, we'll expand our network of cooperative hospitals in Japan's farming villages
Dialogue: 10,0:19:56.66,0:19:59.18,Thought,,0,0,0,,through the industrial cooperatives.
Dialogue: 10,0:19:59.18,0:20:03.34,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Then, on December 17th, 1933, \Nthe Nakano Cooperative Hospital
Dialogue: 10,0:20:03.34,0:20:08.27,Narrator,,0,0,0,,was completed on Miyazono-dori's \N4th Block in Nakano. {https://maps.app.goo.gl/PNKnwRNwZzCttyfg9}
Dialogue: 10,0:20:08.91,0:20:13.75,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Dr. Hirose became the hospital director, and Kurokawa Taiichi took up the role of administrative director.
Dialogue: 10,0:20:13.75,0:20:17.20,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The cooperative already had \N1,500 members in it. {unsure, maybe "the hospital served 1500 members of the coop."}
Dialogue: 10,0:20:17.20,0:20:21.95,Narrator,,0,0,0,,In September 1935, \NNakano Cooperative Hospital expanded,
Dialogue: 10,0:20:21.95,0:20:24.21,Narrator,,0,0,0,,and in November 1938, it became the first
Dialogue: 10,0:20:24.21,0:20:28.29,Narrator,,0,0,0,,of all cooperative medical institutions nationwide to build a maternity ward.
Dialogue: 10,0:20:28.29,0:20:31.53,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Despite persecution from the medical association, it made great strides.
Dialogue: 10,0:20:31.53,0:20:37.10,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa’s vision of creating a model cooperative hospital and promoting it nationwide
Dialogue: 10,0:20:37.10,0:20:39.22,Narrator,,0,0,0,,had come to fruition.
Dialogue: 10,0:20:39.22,0:20:41.51,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Next, Kagawa Toyohiko
Dialogue: 10,0:20:41.51,0:20:45.28,Narrator,,0,0,0,,felt the need to establish a strong mutual aid system for medical expenses,
Dialogue: 10,0:20:45.28,0:20:47.23,Narrator,,0,0,0,,and began laying the groundwork for it.
Dialogue: 10,0:20:47.23,0:20:52.15,Default,,0,0,0,,One for all, and all for one—\Neveryone would pool money together,
Dialogue: 10,0:20:52.15,0:20:54.92,Default,,0,0,0,,and in case of need, draw from that fund \Nto cover medical costs.
Dialogue: 10,0:20:54.92,0:20:57.24,Default,,0,0,0,,This is the mutual aid system \Nwe seek to implement.
Dialogue: 10,0:20:57.24,0:21:00.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Mutual aid associations and insurance systems \Nare well developed in Europe,
Dialogue: 10,0:21:00.66,0:21:03.16,Default,,0,0,0,,but we're not simply going \Nto copy those foreign models.
Dialogue: 10,0:21:03.16,0:21:07.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Our ancestors have had excellent \Nmutual aid systems since ancient times.
Dialogue: 10,0:21:07.60,0:21:11.50,Default,,0,0,0,,In Japan’s villages, there were traditional systems \Nsuch as a mutual financing association​. {頼母子講}{another one he names is "association to co-operate (in enterprises); to hold in common; to share​" but I don't think there's any point to include both}
Dialogue: 10,0:21:11.50,0:21:14.19,Default,,0,0,0,,These were also forms of mutual aid.
Dialogue: 10,0:21:14.19,0:21:19.78,Default,,0,0,0,,In 1839, Ohara Yugaku founded the Ancestral Shareholding Cooperative in Katori, Chiba, {no clue what to make of ancestor here}{https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C5%8Chara_Y%C5%ABgaku}
Dialogue: 10,0:21:19.78,0:21:24.32,Default,,0,0,0,,and in Odawara, Kanagawa, Ninomiya Sontoku \Nestablished the Hotoku Movement. {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ninomiya_Sontoku ; https://www.britannica.com/topic/Hotoku}
Dialogue: 10,0:21:24.32,0:21:28.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Both were homegrown mutual aid systems \Npioneered by local farmers.
Dialogue: 10,0:21:28.29,0:21:30.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Pooling cash is not the only way \Nto do mutual aid.
Dialogue: 10,0:21:30.96,0:21:33.84,Default,,0,0,0,,You can also generate funds \Nthrough joint use of fields,
Dialogue: 10,0:21:33.84,0:21:39.73,Default,,0,0,0,,by contributing rice or wheat in kind, \Nor by making straw crafts to earn income. {lit: straw processed goods; finished goods}
Dialogue: 10,0:21:39.73,0:21:43.00,Default,,0,0,0,,There are countless ways \Nto build a mutual aid fund.
Dialogue: 10,0:21:44.22,0:21:47.94,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa further argued \Nthat cooperative health insurance
Dialogue: 10,0:21:47.94,0:21:52.91,Narrator,,0,0,0,,should not only protect farmers' health \Nthrough comprehensive support,
Dialogue: 10,0:21:52.91,0:21:57.35,Narrator,,0,0,0,,but also serve as a source of capital to invigorate rural economies.
Dialogue: 10,0:21:57.35,0:21:59.18,Thought,,0,0,0,,It's for the farmers...
Dialogue: 10,0:21:59.99,0:22:05.19,Default,,0,0,0,,My cry for medical cooperatives as part of a 100-year national framework stems from this belief. {????}
Dialogue: 10,0:22:05.19,0:22:10.25,Default,,0,0,0,,It's impossible to implement national health insurance \Nwithout raising enough medical cooperatives first. {???}
Dialogue: 10,0:22:10.25,0:22:14.25,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa wrote a social novel \Ncentered around this conviction.
Dialogue: 10,0:22:14.25,0:22:17.94,Narrator,,0,0,0,,He titled it "The Land Where Milk \Nand Honey are Flowing." {like in the bible}
Dialogue: 10,0:22:17.94,0:22:22.97,Narrator,,0,0,0,,It was serialized in the "Light in Home" magazine from January 1934 for two years. {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ie_no_Hikari}
Dialogue: 10,0:22:23.58,0:22:27.11,Narrator,,0,0,0,,It is said that the novel played a key role \Nin propelling "Light in Home"
Dialogue: 10,0:22:27.11,0:22:30.27,Narrator,,0,0,0,,to reach one million copies in circulation.
Dialogue: 10,0:22:30.27,0:22:33.25,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The government too, \Ninfluenced by Kagawa’s activities,
Dialogue: 10,0:22:33.25,0:22:36.86,Narrator,,0,0,0,,began deliberating on the National Health Insurance System.
Dialogue: 10,0:22:36.86,0:22:40.93,Narrator,,0,0,0,,However, the government was only interested \Nin exerting ideological control on the rural areas,
Dialogue: 10,0:22:40.93,0:22:44.80,Narrator,,0,0,0,,and not in implementing the constitutional reforms \Nproposed by the cooperative movement.
Dialogue: 10,0:22:44.80,0:22:49.57,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa and other medical cooperative leaders insisted that the cooperative model be incorporated
Dialogue: 10,0:22:49.57,0:22:52.30,Narrator,,0,0,0,,into the proposed state health insurance plan,
Dialogue: 10,0:22:52.30,0:22:54.91,Narrator,,0,0,0,,and lobbied the Social Bureau \Nof the Home Ministry for it.
Dialogue: 10,0:22:54.91,0:22:57.84,Narrtop,,0,0,0,,As a result, the draft version of the National Health Insurance Law
Dialogue: 10,0:22:57.84,0:23:03.37,Narrtop,,0,0,0,,compiled by the Social Bureau reflected Kagawa’s proposal in Article 9.
Dialogue: 10,0:23:03.37,0:23:08.05,Narrator,,0,0,0,,However, in Seiyoken in Ueno, \NMedical Association officials from all over the country
Dialogue: 10,0:23:08.05,0:23:10.82,Narrator,,0,0,0,,convened an emergency National Physicians’ Congress. {https://maps.app.goo.gl/TYevDUVyeU2jBb7M6}
Dialogue: 10,0:23:10.82,0:23:14.38,Default,,0,0,0,,We will firmly crush any cooperatives' attempts \Nto run national health insurance!
Dialogue: 10,0:23:14.38,0:23:17.38,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The Medical Association's pressure on the government was enormous.
Dialogue: 10,0:23:17.38,0:23:20.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s hold our own congress \Nwith industrial cooperatives! {??}
Dialogue: 10,0:23:20.00,0:23:22.54,Default,,0,0,0,,If the Medical Association \Napplies political pressure,
Dialogue: 10,0:23:22.54,0:23:25.40,Default,,0,0,0,,then the farmers will fight back \Nwith political power too!
Dialogue: 10,0:23:25.40,0:23:32.95,Narrator,,0,0,0,,On March 15th, 1937, a National Rally to Absolutely Support the National Health Insurance Bill
Dialogue: 10,0:23:32.95,0:23:37.08,Narrator,,0,0,0,,was held in Akasaka, Tokyo, organized by the Central Association of Industrial Cooperatives.
Dialogue: 10,0:23:37.08,0:23:42.42,Top,,0,0,0,,All problems facing rural areas \Nmust be resolved through industrial cooperatives!
Dialogue: 10,0:23:42.42,0:23:46.41,Top,,0,0,0,,The association's ambitions for rural healthcare are an unacceptable overreach!
Dialogue: 10,0:23:46.78,0:23:49.78,Narrator,,0,0,0,,After the rally concluded, the cooperative representatives
Dialogue: 10,0:23:49.78,0:23:53.80,Narrator,,0,0,0,,carrying a resolutions in support of the government’s original bill
Dialogue: 10,0:23:53.80,0:23:56.15,Narrator,,0,0,0,,stormed the government \Nand two other ministries. {???}
Dialogue: 10,0:23:56.15,0:24:01.87,Narrator,,0,0,0,,However, just before the bill was to be submitted \Nto the House of Representatives,
Dialogue: 10,0:24:01.87,0:24:05.74,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Prime Minister Hayashi's cabinet \Nsuddenly dissolved the House. {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1937_Japanese_general_election#:~:text=In%20February%201937,ja%5D%22.}
Dialogue: 10,0:24:06.48,0:24:08.81,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The bill ultimately failed to pass.
Dialogue: 10,0:24:09.72,0:24:11.98,Narrtop,,0,0,0,,Following the resignation of the Hayashi Cabinet,
Dialogue: 10,0:24:11.99,0:24:16.19,Narrtop,,0,0,0,,The succeeding administration \Nwas that of Prime Minister Konoe Fumimaro. {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fumimaro_Konoe}
Dialogue: 10,0:24:16.19,0:24:18.63,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The new Minister of Agriculture and Forestry
Dialogue: 10,0:24:18.63,0:24:22.79,Narrator,,0,0,0,,was Arima Yoriyasu, the president \Nof the Industrial Cooperatives Association. {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yoriyasu_Arima}
Dialogue: 10,0:24:22.79,0:24:24.80,Narrtop,,0,0,0,,Because Arima had joined the cabinet,
Dialogue: 10,0:24:24.80,0:24:28.61,Narrtop,,0,0,0,,the medical cooperatives' advocates firmly believed that industrial cooperatives
Dialogue: 10,0:24:28.61,0:24:31.50,Narrtop,,0,0,0,,would take over national \Nhealth insurance operations.
Dialogue: 10,0:24:31.50,0:24:38.41,Narrator,,0,0,0,,However, on July 7th, the second Sino-Japanese war \Nbroke out in Lugouqiao, a suburb of Beijing.
Dialogue: 10,0:24:38.91,0:24:43.47,Narrator,,0,0,0,,With this sudden turn of events, even this council \Npostponed the re-submission of the bill.
Dialogue: 10,0:24:43.47,0:24:48.39,Narrator,,0,0,0,,It wasn’t until January 27th, 1938—\Nwhen the flames of war on the continent
Dialogue: 10,0:24:48.39,0:24:51.59,Narrator,,0,0,0,,were intensifying by the day—\Nthat the revised bill,
Dialogue: 10,0:24:51.59,0:24:57.80,Narrator,,0,0,0,,following coordination within the government, \Nwas finally submitted to the 73rd Diet.
Dialogue: 10,0:24:57.80,0:25:02.33,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The jurisdiction over the bill was transferred from the Ministry of Home Affairs
Dialogue: 10,0:25:02.33,0:25:05.04,Narrator,,0,0,0,,to the newly-established Ministry of Health and Welfare.
Dialogue: 10,0:25:05.04,0:25:07.27,Narrator,,0,0,0,,With that, the industrial cooperatives
Dialogue: 10,0:25:07.27,0:25:11.51,Narrator,,0,0,0,,were officially recognized by the law \Nas representatives of health insurance unions.
Dialogue: 10,0:25:12.28,0:25:16.95,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The realization of a cooperative society supported by love for humanity
Dialogue: 10,0:25:16.95,0:25:21.12,Narrator,,0,0,0,,was rapidly brought closer \Nby this becoming a state-funded project.
Dialogue: 10,0:25:21.69,0:25:27.19,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The number of industrial cooperatives acting as agents for the national health insurance business
Dialogue: 10,0:25:27.19,0:25:30.46,Narrator,,0,0,0,,reached 2,554 across the country.
Dialogue: 10,0:25:30.46,0:25:35.83,Narrator,,0,0,0,,At last, Kagawa secured industrial cooperative management of the national health insurance system.
Dialogue: 10,0:25:35.83,0:25:38.87,Narrator,,0,0,0,,It had been a struggle \Nagainst illness and persecution,
Dialogue: 10,0:25:38.87,0:25:45.76,Narrator,,0,0,0,,but Kagawa seemed to be steadily ascending the stairway to realizing an ideal society. {??}
Dialogue: 10,0:25:45.76,0:25:52.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Japan is now trying to force its way through, \Nbut that is not the fellowship of true Christians.
Dialogue: 10,0:25:52.68,0:25:56.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Even when we are subjected to violence \Nby force, we must endure it.
Dialogue: 10,0:25:56.65,0:25:59.79,Default,,0,0,0,,That is the path to saving the world \Nfrom the destruction of war.
Dialogue: 10,0:25:59.79,0:26:01.49,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The next day, Kagawa was arrested
Dialogue: 10,0:26:01.49,0:26:06.36,Narrator,,0,0,0,,and detained by the Shibuya Military Police \Nfor violating the Military Penal Code.
Dialogue: 10,0:26:06.36,0:26:09.33,Narrator,,0,0,0,,This was due to the government’s outrage
Dialogue: 10,0:26:09.33,0:26:12.57,Narrator,,0,0,0,,over an antiwar commentary he had published in a calendar
Dialogue: 10,0:26:12.57,0:26:14.79,Narrator,,0,0,0,,issued by an American religious organization.
Dialogue: 10,0:26:14.79,0:26:17.91,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa was sent to Sugamo Prison. {eeey second show we're doing about this one too, wink wink}
Dialogue: 10,0:26:18.48,0:26:23.77,Narrator,,0,0,0,,What awaited him there \Nwas the harsh life of a criminal.
Dialogue: 10,0:26:23.77,0:26:26.49,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa endured it by praying to God.
Dialogue: 10,0:26:27.09,0:26:30.12,Narrator,,0,0,0,,He recalled the words of Saint Paul{ Geromini}:
Dialogue: 10,0:26:30.99,0:26:36.20,Narrator,,0,0,0,,“If I think of my life as dying anew every day \Nthrough a life of suffering,
Dialogue: 10,0:26:36.20,0:26:39.78,Narrator,,0,0,0,,then pain and sorrow become a joy.” {cant find this in any version of bible, seems to be kagawa's own interpretation}
Dialogue: 10,0:26:39.78,0:26:42.64,Thought,,0,0,0,,Ah, I die daily... {show's title}
Dialogue: 10,0:26:43.79,0:26:48.61,Narrator,,0,0,0,,In 1941, Japan-US relations \Ngrew worse than ever.
Dialogue: 10,0:26:48.61,0:26:53.38,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Foreign Minister Matsuoka Yosuke had already concluded the Tripartite Pact with Germany and Italy,
Dialogue: 10,0:26:53.38,0:26:56.01,Narrator,,0,0,0,,and also signed \Nthe Japan-Soviet Neutrality Pact.
Dialogue: 10,0:26:56.01,0:26:58.38,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Just as storm clouds \Ngathered on the horizon,
Dialogue: 10,0:26:58.38,0:27:03.02,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa set out for America \Nas a member of a Christian peace mission.
Dialogue: 10,0:27:03.76,0:27:07.79,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Though facilitating Japan–U.S. dialogue \Nwas also part of their mission,
Dialogue: 10,0:27:07.79,0:27:11.81,Narrator,,0,0,0,,it was mostly aimed to explain the wartime position of the United Church of Christ in Japan.
Dialogue: 10,0:27:11.81,0:27:15.47,Narrator,,0,0,0,,In late June, he visited New York,
Dialogue: 10,0:27:15.47,0:27:20.54,Narrator,,0,0,0,,and at the Roosevelt Hotel, a welcome banquet \Nfor Toyohiko Kagawa was held.
Dialogue: 10,0:27:20.54,0:27:23.34,Narrator,,0,0,0,,But the atmosphere was heavy.
Dialogue: 10,0:27:23.34,0:27:26.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Even with such fine hospitality, \NI cannot feel at peace.
Dialogue: 10,0:27:26.68,0:27:30.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Everyone, Japan and the United States \Nare on the brink of war.
Dialogue: 10,0:27:30.85,0:27:35.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Why are we not praying for peace between Japan and the United States?
Dialogue: 10,0:27:35.02,0:27:38.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Now is the time to pray—\Nfor everlasting peace, true peace!
Dialogue: 10,0:27:38.89,0:27:41.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Let us not forget the love of Christ.
Dialogue: 10,0:27:41.16,0:27:43.40,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa’s voice trembled with tears,
Dialogue: 10,0:27:43.40,0:27:46.85,Narrator,,0,0,0,,and the audience, moved beyond national and ethnic borders, was deeply touched.
Dialogue: 10,0:27:47.70,0:27:52.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Let us pray from today, for one week, \Nso that war will not break out
Dialogue: 10,0:27:52.04,0:27:55.24,Default,,0,0,0,,and that peace between Japan and the United States will endure.
Dialogue: 10,0:27:55.86,0:28:00.21,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa gathered fellow church members and began an all-night prayer vigil.
Dialogue: 10,0:28:01.11,0:28:05.82,Narrator,,0,0,0,,A candle lit on December 1st continued to burn for a full week.
Dialogue: 10,0:28:05.82,0:28:08.87,Narrator,,0,0,0,,On the morning of December 8th, \Nwhen that flame finally went out...
Dialogue: 10,0:28:08.87,0:28:13.09,Default,,0,0,0,,A statement from Imperial Headquarters{, Army and Navy sections}, for December 8th, 6 o'clock in the morning,
Dialogue: 10,0:28:13.09,0:28:16.88,Default,,0,0,0,,the Imperial Army and Navy are engaged in combat with{ the American and British armed forces located in the Western Pacific Ocean}...
Dialogue: 10,0:28:16.88,0:28:20.10,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Hiroshima and Nagasaki were eventually \Nstruck with atomic bombs,
Dialogue: 10,0:28:20.10,0:28:22.43,Narrator,,0,0,0,,and the nightmare of war came to an end.
Dialogue: 10,0:28:23.24,0:28:31.24,Narrator,,0,0,0,,August 15, 1945—peace had returned, \Nbut at a tremendous cost.
Dialogue: 10,0:28:31.24,0:28:33.71,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Japan's major cities were reduced to ashes,
Dialogue: 10,0:28:33.71,0:28:38.90,Narrator,,0,0,0,,and ten million of its people had lost their livelihoods \Nand were left wandering the streets. {food, clothing and shelter; necessities of life}{to be left without means of sustenance; to be turned adrift in the streets; to be rendered homeless; to be out in the cold; to be down and out​}
Dialogue: 10,0:28:39.28,0:28:41.59,Narrator,,0,0,0,,On August 28th,
Dialogue: 10,0:28:41.59,0:28:46.89,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa was invited by Prime Minister Higashikuni \Nto the Prime Minister’s residence. {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prince_Naruhiko_Higashikuni#Prime_Minister}
Dialogue: 10,0:28:46.89,0:28:51.90,Top,,0,0,0,,This is a national crisis—defeat, occupation, \Nchaos, and deprivation.
Dialogue: 10,0:28:51.90,0:28:55.60,Default,,0,0,0,,We need a force capable of saving the souls\N of the Japanese people.
Dialogue: 10,0:28:55.60,0:28:59.74,Default,,0,0,0,,That force lies with you, Reverend Kagawa.
Dialogue: 10,0:28:59.74,0:29:04.81,Default,,0,0,0,,The current cabinet alone \Ncannot convince the Americans.
Dialogue: 10,0:29:04.81,0:29:07.78,Default,,0,0,0,,We need someone \Nwho truly understands America.
Dialogue: 10,0:29:07.78,0:29:11.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Reverend Kagawa, please accept a position as advisor to the Higashikuni Cabinet.
Dialogue: 10,0:29:11.95,0:29:14.92,Default,,0,0,0,,I understand your intentions well.
Dialogue: 10,0:29:14.92,0:29:16.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Please allow me some time to think it over.
Dialogue: 10,0:29:16.94,0:29:20.96,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa then consulted \Nwith leaders of the Christian community
Dialogue: 10,0:29:20.96,0:29:23.76,Narrator,,0,0,0,,on what his role as cabinet advisor should be.
Dialogue: 10,0:29:23.76,0:29:28.67,Narrator,,0,0,0,,He proposed that Japan’s defeat \Nstemmed from the fact that its people,
Dialogue: 10,0:29:28.67,0:29:32.11,Narrator,,0,0,0,,both Christians and the general public alike,
Dialogue: 10,0:29:32.11,0:29:37.18,Narrator,,0,0,0,,have been ignorant, indifferent, \Nand overzealous in the past,
Dialogue: 10,0:29:37.18,0:29:42.96,Narrator,,0,0,0,,and now was the time to launch a nationwide “Movement for National Repentance.”
Dialogue: 10,0:29:42.96,0:29:48.19,Narrator,,0,0,0,,On August 30, General MacArthur arrived at Atsugi Airfield.
Dialogue: 10,0:29:48.19,0:29:54.26,Narrator,,0,0,0,,That very day, Kagawa’s open letter to MacArthur was published in the Yomiuri Hochi newspaper. {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yomiuri_Shimbun#:~:text=In%201942%2C%20under%20wartime%20conditions%2C%20it%20merged%20with%20the%20Hochi%20Shimbun%20and%20became%20known%20as%20the%20Yomiuri%2DHochi.}
Dialogue: 10,0:29:54.26,0:29:56.73,Thought,,0,0,0,,To Supreme Commander MacArthur:
Dialogue: 10,0:29:56.73,0:30:01.10,Thought,,0,0,0,,On August 15, Japan accepted defeat and fell under the shadow of loss.
Dialogue: 10,0:30:01.10,0:30:04.84,Thought,,0,0,0,,Now, the victorious nations must act \Nwith great magnanimity and compassion.
Dialogue: 10,0:30:04.84,0:30:10.58,Thought,,0,0,0,,Japan stands ready to embark on a new path \Nas a responsible member of the world community.
Dialogue: 10,0:30:11.04,0:30:14.05,Thought,,0,0,0,,To confine her within narrow limits without cause
Dialogue: 10,0:30:14.05,0:30:17.55,Thought,,0,0,0,,will only produce results \Nfar removed from your noble ideals.
Dialogue: 10,0:30:17.55,0:30:21.12,Thought,,0,0,0,,I ask you, sir, to bring out \Nthe best of the Japanese character
Dialogue: 10,0:30:21.12,0:30:25.76,Thought,,0,0,0,,and spur Japan forward \Ntoward a new culture and a new world—
Dialogue: 10,0:30:25.76,0:30:28.03,Thought,,0,0,0,,with a kind heart and not a sword. {lit: not by wielding the whip of the katana - think he means "not by whipping japan into in by force, but by persuasion" or something}
Dialogue: 10,0:30:28.98,0:30:33.60,Narrator,,0,0,0,,With the return of peace, Kagawa Toyohiko found himself in the national spotlight.
Dialogue: 10,0:30:33.60,0:30:37.99,Narrator,,0,0,0,,On October 5, 1945, \Nthe Higashikuni Cabinet resigned in full.
Dialogue: 10,0:30:37.99,0:30:41.54,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The following day, a secretary to elder statesman Ozaki Yukio
Dialogue: 10,0:30:41.54,0:30:45.84,Narrator,,0,0,0,,visited Kagawa’s home in Kamikitazawa \Nwith three candidacies for the next prime minister:
Dialogue: 10,0:30:45.84,0:30:51.00,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Shidehara Kijuro, Yoshida Shigeru, \Nand Kagawa Toyohiko.
Dialogue: 10,0:30:51.00,0:30:55.02,Default,,0,0,0,,I already have work that serves God, \Nand I am committed to the cooperative movement.
Dialogue: 10,0:30:55.02,0:30:57.01,Default,,0,0,0,,I have no desire to become prime minister.
Dialogue: 10,0:30:57.01,0:31:01.06,Narrator,,0,0,0,,In 1946, he was appointed to the House of Peers,
Dialogue: 10,0:31:01.06,0:31:04.43,Narrator,,0,0,0,,but there’s an anecdote that he never once \Nstepped foot in the Diet building.
Dialogue: 10,0:31:04.43,0:31:07.10,Narrator,,0,0,0,,One must also remember Kagawa’s key role
Dialogue: 10,0:31:07.10,0:31:10.57,Narrator,,0,0,0,,in the founding of the Japan Socialist Party.
Dialogue: 10,0:31:10.57,0:31:18.78,Narrator,,0,0,0,,In the fall of 1945, socialist leaders such as Abe Isoo \Nand Takano Iwasaburo joined Kagawa
Dialogue: 10,0:31:18.78,0:31:23.62,Narrator,,0,0,0,,in rallying former members \Nof the Labor and Social Democratic parties.
Dialogue: 10,0:31:23.62,0:31:26.95,Narrator,,0,0,0,,At the Kuramae Industrial Hall in Shinbashi, {can't find it now}
Dialogue: 10,0:31:26.95,0:31:32.26,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Matsuoka Komakichi, Katayama Tetsu, \NKawakami Jotaro, Sugiyama Motojiro,
Dialogue: 10,0:31:32.26,0:31:38.05,Narrator,,0,0,0,,and Nishio Suehiro—around 200 figures total, \Ngathered to discuss the party’s formation.
Dialogue: 10,0:31:38.66,0:31:44.57,Narrtop,,0,0,0,,The founding ceremony was held \Non November 2, 1945, at Hibiya Public Hall.
Dialogue: 10,0:31:44.57,0:31:47.06,Narrtop,,0,0,0,,Tetsu Katayama was chosen as the first party leader.
Dialogue: 10,0:31:47.06,0:31:53.21,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Now in the political spotlight, Kagawa \Nstepped down from his advisory role in the cabinet
Dialogue: 10,0:31:53.21,0:31:57.38,Narrator,,0,0,0,,and threw himself into leading the Movement for National Repentance.
Dialogue: 10,0:31:57.38,0:32:03.07,Narrator,,0,0,0,,He also served a crucial role as a mediator between the Japanese public and GHQ.
Dialogue: 10,0:32:03.49,0:32:05.86,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Though the country was broken, \Nits people remained,
Dialogue: 10,0:32:05.86,0:32:10.36,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Japan’s cities lay in ruin, \Nand the countryside fared little better.
Dialogue: 10,0:32:10.70,0:32:14.83,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The war had devastated the agricultural technology \Nthat sustained food production,
Dialogue: 10,0:32:14.83,0:32:18.02,Narrator,,0,0,0,,and defeat had left farmers \Nin a state of total bewilderment. {state of lethargy; absolute bewilderment; daze; mental numbness}
Dialogue: 10,0:32:18.02,0:32:21.87,Narrator,,0,0,0,,At that time, men who had once \Npoured their hearts
Dialogue: 10,0:32:21.87,0:32:25.24,Narrator,,0,0,0,,into farmers’ movements, health co-ops, \Nand consumer cooperatives
Dialogue: 10,0:32:25.24,0:32:30.04,Narrator,,0,0,0,,began gathering at the United Church \Nof Christ in Japan in Kanda.
Dialogue: 10,0:32:30.04,0:32:34.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s rebuild Japan on the foundation \Nof the cooperative movement!
Dialogue: 10,0:32:34.25,0:32:37.29,Default,,0,0,0,,I’ve visited several \NEuropean countries over the years,
Dialogue: 10,0:32:37.29,0:32:39.96,Default,,0,0,0,,and {I can say with conviction that }wherever a defeated nation was rebuilt,
Dialogue: 10,0:32:39.96,0:32:43.06,Default,,0,0,0,,it was through the power \Nof the cooperative movement.
Dialogue: 10,0:32:43.06,0:32:46.33,Narrator,,0,0,0,,From these talks, an organizational framework began to take shape,
Dialogue: 10,0:32:46.33,0:32:51.47,Narrator,,0,0,0,,and on November 18th, 1945, \Nthe Japan Cooperative League
Dialogue: 10,0:32:51.47,0:32:55.06,Narrator,,0,0,0,,was officially established \Nat the Kuramae Industrial Hall in Shimbashi.
Dialogue: 10,0:32:55.06,0:33:01.35,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Meanwhile, in November 1947, \Nthe Diet passed the Agricultural Cooperatives Act.
Dialogue: 10,0:33:01.35,0:33:05.07,Narrator,,0,0,0,,This law formally allowed cooperative insurance programs.
Dialogue: 10,0:33:05.07,0:33:10.92,Narrator,,0,0,0,,In the years that followed, 28,500 agricultural cooperatives sprang up in rural areas across Japan.
Dialogue: 10,0:33:10.92,0:33:13.46,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa’s long-held dream \Nof cooperative insurance
Dialogue: 10,0:33:13.46,0:33:17.05,Narrator,,0,0,0,,began to take form \Nas agricultural cooperative insurance.
Dialogue: 10,0:33:17.05,0:33:20.80,Narrator,,0,0,0,,But opposition from the insurance industry \Ncame as no surprise.
Dialogue: 10,0:33:20.80,0:33:25.05,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Insurance salesmen \Nbegan scrambling to rural households.
Dialogue: 10,0:33:25.05,0:33:28.67,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Additionally, some voices from within \Nthe rural sector pushed back.
Dialogue: 10,0:33:29.31,0:33:32.54,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The existing Agricultural Mutual Relief Associations were far from quiet.
Dialogue: 10,0:33:32.54,0:33:34.75,Default,,0,0,0,,We’re the senior organization in agri-insurance!
Dialogue: 10,0:33:34.75,0:33:37.12,Default,,0,0,0,,There’s no reason \Nfor the new co-ops to go that far!
Dialogue: 10,0:33:37.12,0:33:39.75,Default,,0,0,0,,We have the backing \Nof the national government!
Dialogue: 10,0:33:40.07,0:33:43.86,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The newborn agricultural cooperative insurance program found itself surrounded—
Dialogue: 10,0:33:43.86,0:33:45.83,Narrator,,0,0,0,,boxed in by the commercial insurance sector,
Dialogue: 10,0:33:45.83,0:33:49.70,Narrator,,0,0,0,,the Mutual Relief Associations, \Nand government ministries aligned with them.
Dialogue: 10,0:33:49.70,0:33:52.66,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Its very survival hung by a thread.
Dialogue: 10,0:33:54.28,0:33:59.80,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Then—on May 9th, 1948, \Nat the Matsuzawa Church in Kamikitazawa,
Dialogue: 10,0:33:59.80,0:34:03.01,Narrator,,0,0,0,,a ceremony was held marking 40 years since Kagawa Toyohiko
Dialogue: 10,0:34:03.01,0:34:05.98,Narrator,,0,0,0,,began his ministry, \Nas well as his 60th birthday.
Dialogue: 10,0:34:05.98,0:34:08.30,Narrator,,0,0,0,,And after a solemn prayer...
Dialogue: 10,0:34:08.30,0:34:13.56,Default,,0,0,0,,On this occasion, \NI’d like to leave you all with my will.
Dialogue: 10,0:34:13.56,0:34:17.32,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Among the dozen or so wishes in his will, one stood out:
Dialogue: 10,0:34:17.32,0:34:21.30,Default,,0,0,0,,I ask you—make cooperative insurance a reality.
Dialogue: 10,0:34:21.30,0:34:24.03,Default,,0,0,0,,For cooperatives to demonstrate \Ntheir true strength,
Dialogue: 10,0:34:24.03,0:34:29.17,Default,,0,0,0,,we must establish life insurance programs that build long-term, stable reserves.
Dialogue: 10,0:34:29.72,0:34:35.01,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Although the Agricultural Cooperatives Act had passed and the way was clear for cooperative insurance,
Dialogue: 10,0:34:35.01,0:34:39.98,Narrator,,0,0,0,,even the co-op members—let alone officials at the Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry—
Dialogue: 10,0:34:39.98,0:34:45.15,Narrator,,0,0,0,,had only a vague understanding \Nof what co-op insurance actually meant.
Dialogue: 10,0:34:46.42,0:34:48.12,Narrator,,0,0,0,,In this environment,
Dialogue: 10,0:34:48.12,0:34:52.66,Narrator,,0,0,0,,it was Hokkaido that took the initiative \Nin agricultural cooperative mutual aid.
Dialogue: 10,0:34:53.36,0:34:59.33,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The Hokkaido Federation of Agricultural Cooperative Insurance Associations was the first to be established.
Dialogue: 10,0:35:00.03,0:35:09.64,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The national federation didn’t come into being \Nuntil much later—January 31, 1951.
Dialogue: 10,0:35:09.64,0:35:14.98,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Even then, the newly formed \Nnational federation lacked its own offices
Dialogue: 10,0:35:14.98,0:35:17.88,Narrator,,0,0,0,,and was crammed into a corner of a building in Nishi-Ginza,
Dialogue: 10,0:35:17.88,0:35:21.35,Narrator,,0,0,0,,sharing space with other national agricultural cooperative federations.
Dialogue: 10,0:35:21.35,0:35:26.32,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Its first president was Okamura Bunshiro, \Nhead of Hokkaido’s agricultural federation.
Dialogue: 10,0:35:26.32,0:35:31.65,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Yamanaka Ryozo, head of the Hokkaido insurance federation, was appointed executive director.
Dialogue: 10,0:35:31.65,0:35:35.30,Narrator,,0,0,0,,How were they to nurture \Nthis besieged initiative?
Dialogue: 10,0:35:35.30,0:35:37.65,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The leadership fought desperately \Nto keep it alive.
Dialogue: 10,0:35:37.65,0:35:40.71,Narrator,,0,0,0,,From July 14th, 1952,
Dialogue: 10,0:35:40.71,0:35:45.06,Narrator,,0,0,0,,the first leadership seminar for agricultural cooperative insurance
Dialogue: 10,0:35:45.06,0:35:47.88,Narrator,,0,0,0,,was held in Koganei City, Tokyo.
Dialogue: 10,0:35:47.88,0:35:53.85,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Most participants were prefectural staffers with no knowledge even of the insurance program’s basics.
Dialogue: 10,0:35:53.85,0:35:58.67,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa Toyohiko drilled his cooperative insurance philosophy into their heads:
Dialogue: 10,0:35:58.67,0:36:00.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Private insurers operate for profit!
Dialogue: 10,0:36:00.99,0:36:06.00,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s why they avoid insuring people \Nor regions with high risk—
Dialogue: 10,0:36:06.00,0:36:09.33,Default,,0,0,0,,say, farmers living under \Ndilapidated thatched roofs.
Dialogue: 10,0:36:09.33,0:36:11.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Cooperative insurance is different.
Dialogue: 10,0:36:11.84,0:36:14.41,Default,,0,0,0,,It exists to protect everyone.
Dialogue: 10,0:36:14.41,0:36:18.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Its aim is to reinvest profits back into society \Nand function as a safeguard
Dialogue: 10,0:36:18.74,0:36:21.65,Default,,0,0,0,,that prevents disaster before it strikes.
Dialogue: 10,0:36:21.65,0:36:25.38,Default,,0,0,0,,This social reinvestment \Nis what benefits the members.
Dialogue: 10,0:36:25.38,0:36:30.29,Default,,0,0,0,,In other words, whether cooperatives \Ncan help solve the root of society’s problems
Dialogue: 10,0:36:30.29,0:36:34.99,Default,,0,0,0,,depends on how insurance profits \Nare returned to the public.
Dialogue: 10,0:36:34.99,0:36:38.71,Default,,0,0,0,,To put it differently—Japan is still reeling \Nfrom the devastation of war,
Dialogue: 10,0:36:38.71,0:36:43.10,Default,,0,0,0,,and countless social problems \Nremain unsolved.
Dialogue: 10,0:36:43.10,0:36:47.31,Default,,0,0,0,,So I say this: Cooperative insurance \Nis the fundamental path to saving Japan.
Dialogue: 10,0:36:47.72,0:36:51.24,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa once again traveled from one agricultural cooperative to another,
Dialogue: 10,0:36:51.24,0:36:55.73,Narrator,,0,0,0,,explaining to the members that cooperative insurance was a national salvation movement.
Dialogue: 10,0:36:55.73,0:37:00.09,Default,,0,0,0,,My friends, if life insurance through cooperatives reaches farming families across Japan,
Dialogue: 10,0:37:00.09,0:37:02.25,Default,,0,0,0,,this nation will rise again with dignity.
Dialogue: 10,0:37:02.25,0:37:06.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Even if Japan should face \Ndevastation again someday,
Dialogue: 10,0:37:06.16,0:37:10.09,Default,,0,0,0,,as long as life insurance exists, \Nit will rise from the ashes like a phoenix. {it's like he heard about https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ph%C3%B6nix-Skandal}
Dialogue: 10,0:37:10.09,0:37:13.75,Default,,0,0,0,,I’ve seen this firsthand \Nin countries around the world.
Dialogue: 10,0:37:13.75,0:37:18.94,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa’s impassioned appeals resonated deeply \Nwith the cooperative members,
Dialogue: 10,0:37:18.94,0:37:23.76,Narrator,,0,0,0,,instilling courage and hope in farmers and villages still reeling from the war.
Dialogue: 10,0:37:24.34,0:37:29.76,Narrator,,0,0,0,,He also explained the essence of cooperatives and mutual aid in his own distinct style:
Dialogue: 10,0:37:29.76,0:37:32.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Cooperatives are the backbone of a nation.
Dialogue: 10,0:37:32.28,0:37:35.89,Default,,0,0,0,,And life insurance \Nis the spine of those cooperatives.
Dialogue: 10,0:37:35.89,0:37:39.22,Default,,0,0,0,,If we think of a nation as a human body, \Nthe brain is the government.
Dialogue: 10,0:37:39.22,0:37:45.36,Default,,0,0,0,,But the heart, stomach, liver, and muscles are all different types of cooperatives.
Dialogue: 10,0:37:45.36,0:37:48.90,Default,,0,0,0,,The stomach is the consumer cooperative; the muscles are the producer cooperative.
Dialogue: 10,0:37:48.90,0:37:52.00,Default,,0,0,0,,In other words, production, sales, purchasing,
Dialogue: 10,0:37:52.00,0:37:57.14,Default,,0,0,0,,and credit cooperatives together \Nmake up the nation which is a human body.
Dialogue: 10,0:37:57.14,0:38:02.58,Default,,0,0,0,,With the addition of life insurance, \Nthe body finally stands upright.
Dialogue: 10,0:38:02.58,0:38:07.12,Default,,0,0,0,,A cooperative without life insurance \Nis like a jellyfish—spineless and shapeless.
Dialogue: 10,0:38:07.12,0:38:09.79,Default,,0,0,0,,And a nation without cooperatives is the same.
Dialogue: 10,0:38:09.79,0:38:14.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Life insurance gives cooperatives their backbone—\Nit turns them into vertebrates.
Dialogue: 10,0:38:15.29,0:38:21.20,Narrator,,0,0,0,,In June 1954, an awards ceremony was held in the hall of the Norinchukin Bank in Marunouchi, Tokyo,
Dialogue: 10,0:38:21.20,0:38:24.82,Narrator,,0,0,0,,honoring agricultural cooperatives \Nwith outstanding records in life insurance.
Dialogue: 10,0:38:24.82,0:38:27.87,Default,,0,0,0,,If you all continue this cooperative insurance movement,
Dialogue: 10,0:38:27.87,0:38:30.04,Default,,0,0,0,,poverty will vanish \Nfrom Japan’s farming villages.
Dialogue: 10,0:38:30.04,0:38:34.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Japan is the only country in the world that once banned cooperative insurance.
Dialogue: 10,0:38:35.61,0:38:38.05,Default,,0,0,0,,Our rural areas suffered under the burden
Dialogue: 10,0:38:38.05,0:38:42.82,Default,,0,0,0,,of high taxes and fees, while private insurers siphoned off cash from the countryside.
Dialogue: 10,0:38:42.82,0:38:46.59,Default,,0,0,0,,But this agricultural cooperative insurance program, \Nfinally permitted after the war,
Dialogue: 10,0:38:46.59,0:38:49.09,Default,,0,0,0,,will become a mighty force for rural revival.
Dialogue: 10,0:38:49.09,0:38:52.85,Default,,0,0,0,,I earnestly hope all of you will join this movement across the nation.
Dialogue: 10,0:38:52.85,0:38:58.60,Narrtop,,0,0,0,,{\fade(800,0)}Kagawa’s passion stirred agricultural leaders \Nand members alike nationwide,
Dialogue: 10,0:38:58.60,0:39:01.81,Narrtop,,0,0,0,,and the cooperative insurance program \Nexperienced explosive growth.
Dialogue: 10,0:39:02.67,0:39:08.48,Narrtop,,0,0,0,,By the end of fiscal year 1954, \Nthere were 250,000 long-term policies in force. {policy as in "A contract of insurance"}
Dialogue: 10,0:39:08.48,0:39:12.56,Narrtop,,0,0,0,,By 1960, that number had ballooned to 4.76 million—
Dialogue: 10,0:39:12.56,0:39:15.79,Narrtop,,0,0,0,,a 19-fold increase in just six years.
Dialogue: 10,0:39:16.62,0:39:20.13,Narrtop,,0,0,0,,And the growth didn’t stop there.
Dialogue: 10,0:39:21.34,0:39:29.17,Narrtop,,0,0,0,,At the end of fiscal year 1959, the combined value of long-term policies stood at 668.7 billion yen;
Dialogue: 10,0:39:29.17,0:39:33.10,Narrtop,,0,0,0,,by the end of 1960, it reached 960 billion yen;
Dialogue: 10,0:39:33.10,0:39:36.71,Narrtop,,0,0,0,,{\fade(0,800)}and by June of the following year, \Nit had surpassed the 1 trillion yen mark.
Dialogue: 10,0:39:36.96,0:39:43.35,Narrator,,0,0,0,,In January 1956, the National Mutual Insurance Federation of Agricultural Cooperatives
Dialogue: 10,0:39:43.35,0:39:46.85,Narrator,,0,0,0,,launched a five-year plan \Nfor cooperative insurance:
Dialogue: 10,0:39:46.85,0:39:52.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Enroll farming households nationwide and reach 400 billion yen in total life insurance coverage.
Dialogue: 10,0:39:52.94,0:39:58.50,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Ahead of the campaign, Kurokawa Daichi, \Ndirector of the Federation’s operations department,
Dialogue: 10,0:39:58.50,0:40:03.13,Narrator,,0,0,0,,decided a powerful poster \Nwas needed to promote the initiative.
Dialogue: 10,0:40:03.13,0:40:07.99,Narrator,,0,0,0,,He planned to print a slogan in Kagawa’s own handwriting and distribute it to co-ops nationwide.
Dialogue: 10,0:40:07.99,0:40:13.55,Narrator,,0,0,0,,On New Year’s Day, 1956, Kurokawa visited Kagawa’s home in Kamikitazawa:
Dialogue: 10,0:40:13.55,0:40:17.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Sensei, would you give us some words to serve \Nas the backbone of the co-op insurance program?
Dialogue: 10,0:40:17.32,0:40:20.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Certainly! I'd be happy to write it for you.
Dialogue: 10,0:40:20.82,0:40:25.02,Default,,0,0,0,,“Japan’s recovery \Nbegins with life insurance...”
Dialogue: 10,0:40:25.49,0:40:30.26,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The slogan was printed and sent to co-ops and prefectural unions across the country.
Dialogue: 10,0:40:30.26,0:40:36.62,Default,,0,0,0,,"Rural revitalization begins with long-term financing \Nby cooperative auxiliary organizations."
Dialogue: 10,0:40:36.62,0:40:42.02,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The original writing is still displayed today \Nin the Federation’s boardroom.
Dialogue: 10,0:40:42.61,0:40:46.34,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The first signs of Kagawa Toyohiko’s \Nfatal illness appeared
Dialogue: 10,0:40:46.34,0:40:49.31,Narrator,,0,0,0,,while he was traveling on a ship \Nfrom Kobe to Takamatsu.
Dialogue: 10,0:40:50.55,0:40:55.19,Narrator,,0,0,0,,He had set out for his hometown of Tokushima \Nto preach and give lectures,
Dialogue: 10,0:40:55.19,0:40:57.29,Narrator,,0,0,0,,but just before reaching Tokushima,
Dialogue: 10,0:40:57.29,0:41:00.86,Narrator,,0,0,0,,he collapsed and was rushed \Nto St. Luke’s Hospital in Takamatsu.
Dialogue: 10,0:41:01.86,0:41:05.50,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The date was January 6th, 1959.
Dialogue: 10,0:41:07.03,0:41:11.30,Narrator,,0,0,0,,He was diagnosed with myocardial infarction, \Npleural thickening, cardiac hypertrophy—
Dialogue: 10,0:41:11.30,0:41:13.60,Narrator,,0,0,0,,seven serious conditions in all.
Dialogue: 10,0:41:14.71,0:41:18.51,Narrator,,0,0,0,,In the spring, when he stabilized, \Nhe returned to his home in Kamikitazawa. {/when his symptoms were gone}
Dialogue: 10,0:41:18.51,0:41:21.75,Narrator,,0,0,0,,About a month into his home care,
Dialogue: 10,0:41:21.75,0:41:26.52,Narrator,,0,0,0,,he developed pneumonia and was admitted \Nto Nakano Cooperative Hospital.
Dialogue: 10,0:41:32.19,0:41:36.96,Thought,,0,0,0,,I'd like to try going to a hot spring sanatorium in Izu-Nagaoka...
Dialogue: 10,0:41:37.80,0:41:42.83,Narrator,,0,0,0,,At 9:10 p.m. on April 23rd, 1960,
Dialogue: 10,0:41:43.37,0:41:46.74,Narrator,,0,0,0,,Kagawa Toyohiko passed away at his home in Kamikitazawa,
Dialogue: 10,0:41:46.74,0:41:50.37,Narrator,,0,0,0,,concluding his 72-year life on earth \Nand ascending to heaven.
Dialogue: 10,0:41:52.11,0:41:54.75,Narrator,,0,0,0,,The giant's final testament— {giant; great man}{/last will}
Dialogue: 10,0:41:54.75,0:41:59.55,Narrator,,0,0,0,,"Bring cooperative insurance into reality"—\Nwas already realized,
Dialogue: 10,0:41:59.55,0:42:03.12,Narrator,,0,0,0,,and he ascended \Nwhile witnessing its dramatic progress.
